         b'able><!--mstheme--><font face="Arial, Helvetica">\r\n\r\n<p>An ideal'
         b' light field is a function L(p,<font face="Symbol">w,</font>t) t'
         b'hat\r\ngives the radiance at every point p for every direction <fo'
         b'nt face="Symbol">w </font>at\r\ntime t in a space, also called a <'
         b'i>lumigraph</i>. Complete knowledge of this\r\nfunction for a scen'
         b'e would provide a total solution to the problem of computer\r\ngra'
         b'phics rendering of the scene, as it changes through time.&nbsp;<'
         b'/p>\r\n<p>In practice the function L is sampled with a discrete se'
         b't of straight line\r\nrays at a specific time instant. This sample'
         b' of rays, each carrying a radiance\r\nvalue, is what is usually re'
         b"ferred to as a 'light field' [1][2]. In practice\r\nsuch a discret"
         b'e light field is typically obtained from a large set of images,\r'
         b'\ncreated from known camera positions. The technique is used most'
         b' commonly with\r\ndigitally captured images of real scenes, and th'
         b'e light field can then be used\r\nto render these scenes from came'
         b'ra orientations and positions not included in\r\nthe original set.'
         b' The technique may also be used for synthetic scenes - where a\r\n'
         b'large number of images are created using a rendering system such as '
         b'ray tracing,\r\nand then new interpolated images can be reconstruc'
         b'ted from the light field. When\r\nused for synthetic scenes we ref'
         b'er to a <i>virtual light field</i>. This term\r\nwas probably firs'
         b"t used by Gortler et. al. in [1].</p>\r\n<p>Here the term 'virtual"
         b" light field' is extended to mean a rendering system\r\nwhere the "
         b'light field is constructed for a synthetic scene, but without the us'
         b"e\r\nof a separate rendering system. The scene is 'rendered' into "
         b'a light field in\r\nsuch a way that the radiance values are comput'
         b'ed directly during the\r\nconstruction of the light field itself. '
         b'It turns out that this approach supports\r\nthe creation of a ligh'
         b't field function which intrinsically generates&nbsp;\r\nglobal ill'
         b'umination, with a mix of specularly and diffusely reflecting\r\nma'
         b'terials. Moreover, having created such a light field it can be rende'
         b'red into a\r\n2D image either in the traditional way through a pin'
         b'-hole camera, or by allowing\r\nthe rays to pass through a lens sy'
         b'stem forming an image on an image plane - thus\r\nincluding depth '
         b'of field effects.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>A first attempt to implement a'
         b' virtual light field approach is described in\r\n[3]. That approac'
         b'h resulted in poor images, which nevertheless showed the\r\npromis'
         b'e of the technique for global illumination. The major problem was th'
         b'e\r\nmassive memory required, and the lack of accuracy in visibili'
         b'ty of rays between\r\nobjects.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Since then several it'
         b'erations of the algorithm and implementation have been\r\ncarried '
         b'out, with a vast increase in quality and performance.&nbsp;</p>\r'
         b'\n\r\n\r\n<p>This research is supported by an&nbsp; EPSRC\r\nSenior'
         b' Fellowship Award, and an EPSRC project.</p>\r\n<p>[1] Gortler, S.'
         b', Grzeszczuk, R., Szeliski, R., Cohen, M. (1996) The Lumigraph,\r'
         b'\nComputer Graphics (SIGGRAPH), Annual Conference Series, 43-52.<'
         b'/p>\r\n<p>[2] Levoy M and Hanrahan, P. (1996) Light Field Renderin'
         b'g, Computer Graphics\r\n(SIGGRAPH), Annual Conference Series, 31-4'
         b'2.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[3] M. Slater (2000) <a href="vlfpaper.pdf">A Note '
         b'on Virtual\r\nLight Fields</a>  (PDF), Department of Computer Scie'
         b'nce Research Note RN/00/26/\r\nApril 5th 2000, University College '
         b'London.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3><!--mstheme--><font color="#003333">F'
